INSERT INTO `notes_engl` VALUES (1,'#Adjective or #adverb #english #lh_7(good)','\n\n1) He  xxxxxxxxxxx reads a book. (quick)	\n2) Mandy is a  xxxxxxxxxx girl. 	(pretty)\n3) The class is  xxxxxxxxxxxx loud today. (terrible)	\n4) Max is a  xxxxxxxxx singer. (good)	\n5) You can  xxxxxxxxxxx open this tin. 	(easy)\n6) It\'s a  xxxxxxxxxxxx day today. 	(good)\n7) She sings the song  xxxxxxxx. (good)\n8) He is a  xxxxxxxxxxxxx driver. 	(careful)\n9) He drives the car  xxxxxxxxxxxx. 	(careful)\n10) The dog barks  xxxxxxxxxx. (loud)\n','\n\nquickly\npretty\nterrible\ngood\neasily\ngood\nwell\ncareful\ncarefully\nloudly\n'),(2,'Adjectives - Comparison #english #lh_9(many)','\nPositive	Comparative	   Superlative\n======================================\nfull 		\npoor 		\nheavy 		\nhard 		\ncool 		\nlazy 		\nclear 		\nmodern 		\nmany 		\ncrazy\n','\nfuller 	fullest\npoorer 	poorest\nheavier 	heaviest\nharder 	hardest\ncooler 	coolest\nlazier 	laziest\nclearer 	clearest\nmore modern 	most modern\nmore 	most\ncrazier 	craziest \n'),(3,'#english #countable#noun','\nCan you count the following nouns? Choose the correct answer.\n\nExample: chess - ______\n\nAnswer: chess - uncountable\n\n\n\n1) rice -\n2) potato -\n3) information -\n4) man -\n5) bread -\n6) coffee -\n7) mile -\n8) vegetable -\n9) weather -\n10) sheep -\n\n','\n1) rice -  uncountable \n2) potato -  countable \n3) information -  uncountable \n4) man -  countable \n5) bread -  uncountable \n6) coffee -  uncountable \n7) mile -  countable \n8) vegetable -  countable\n9) weather -  uncountable \n10) sheep -  countable\n'),(4,'#english #grammar #countable#noun','\nAre the following English nouns countable? Choose countable or uncountable.\n\nExample: equipment - __________\n\nAnswer: equipment - uncountable\n\n\n\n1) luck -\n2) permission -\n3) ox -\n4) work -\n5) salmon -\n6) crisis -\n7) baggage -\n8) research -\n9) aircraft -\n10) rubbish -\n','1) luck -  uncountable \n2) permission -  uncountable \n3) ox -  countable \n4) work -  uncountable \n5) salmon -  countable \n6) crisis -  uncountable Correct answer: crisis - countable\n7) baggage -  countable Correct answer: baggage - uncountable\n8) research -  uncountable \n9) aircraft -  countable \n10) rubbish -  uncountable '),(5,'#lesson #make#do',NULL,'\nIt can be hard to decide when to use _make_ or _do_ in English. Here_s some help.\n\n1: We use _make_ when we create or construct something. For example:\n\n    She made a cake.\n    I_ve made us some coffee.\n    Did you really make those trousers?\n\n2: We use _do_ for general activities. In this case, _do_ is often used with _something_, _nothing_, _anything_ or _everything_:\n\n    What did you do at the weekend?\n    I didn_t do anything yesterday.\n    She_s fed up with doing everything herself. She needs some help.\n    Are you doing anything interesting during the holidays?\n\nNOTE: _What do you do?_ means _what_s your job?_\n\n3: There are many, many fixed expressions with _make_ and _do_. Unfortunately, they don_t really follow any useful rules, so you have to learn them. Sorry!\n\nHere_s a list:\n  www.perfect-english-grammar.com/make-or-do.html\nOR\n  table(notes_engl)col(id_e=7)'),(6,'#make#do #lesson#long#list',NULL,'\nDO:\n	30 mph (miles per hour) 	Many people do more than 30 mph through this town. It_s very dangerous.\n	badly 	She did very badly on the exam, so she_ll have to retake it.\n	your best 	Don_t worry about getting everything correct. Just do your best.\n	business 	It_s been a pleasure doing business with you.\n	chores 	I have to go home and do some chores this afternoon.\n	a course 	John has decided to do a course in computing this autumn.\n	a crossword 	She sat on the sofa, doing a crossword and drinking tea.\n	damage 	The storm has done a lot of damage to the house.\n	the dishes / the washing up 	I really hate doing the dishes. I_m hoping to buy a dishwasher this year.\n	a drawing 	The little boy spent hours doing a drawing.\n	your duty 	He has to do